Dabigatran -> Thrombin inhibitor (antidote:idarucizumab)
Rivaroxaban, apixaban and edoxaban -> the factor Xa inhibitors. (antidote andexanet)

  • More predictable rise of INR - administered at fixed dose and do not need monitoring.
  • Fewer interactions.
  • rapid onset and short half-lives - no need for periprocedural bridging.
  • Reversing agents not readily available - except for idarucizumab for dabigatran; (but not a problem due to short half life)
  • renal impairment requires dose adjustment.
  • Dabigatran crosses the placenta: avoid in #pregnancy
  • prosthetic valve
  • eGFR < 30.

Folate defiency = NO NEUROPATHY


Changes seen in B12 deficiency (clockwise from top left)

  1. hypercellular marrow with megaloblastic precursors
  2. Glossitis with hyperpigmentation
  3. Macroovalocytes with hypersegmented neutrophiles
  4. Megaloblasts in the bone marrow aspirates

Features of B12 deficiency neuropathy:

  • Neuropathic features are commoner in B12 deficiency than in B9 deficiency.
    • Shows sensory and motor features;
    • posterior columns first -> then lateral columns
    • Neuropathy is symmetrical, involves legs > arms and causes paraesthesia and gait problems.
    • The classic finding is subacute combined dengeneration of the spinal cord.
      • This leads to demyelination of the dorsal and lateral white matter. (i.e tracts).
      • Leading to sensory (paraesthesia, sensory ataxia) and motor (weakness, spacticity, paraplegia and incontinence).
    • Advanced neurologic changes include paranoia, delirium and confusion.
  • B12 = cobalamin.
  • B12 is only made by some microorganisms; humans are dependent on animal sources.
    • Vegans are at risk of deficiency!
  • The human liver has about 2 years of B12 stores.

Diagnosis of B12 deficiency

  • Blood picture will show macroovalocytes and hypersegmented neutrophils
  • Diagnosis confirmed by measuring on serum B12 levels.
  • Schilling test (now superseded) uses oral radiolabeled B12 to determine if there is absorption defect (i.e if pernicious anaemia is suspected). Usually done only in young patients.
    • Instead we now directly assay antibodies to intrinsic factor
  • Bone marrow biopsy is usually not indicated but features include
    • Bone marrow hypercellularity
    • megaloblastic erythroid hyperplasia
    • Giant metamyelocytes
  • Age related decrease in acid secretion can impair B12 absorption.

" Folate (folic acid) should not be used instead of vitamin B12 because folate may alleviate the anemia but allow neurologic deficits to progress." - Source

Acquired disease (but presents in 30s and 40s) -> a red cell clonal population with the gene mutation develops.
Mutation of PIG-A gene causing reduced expression of PIG-A protein.
It anchors complement resisting proteins (CD55 and CD59) which protect the red cell against complement.

  • Pancytopenia due to marrow suppression (aplastic anaemia)
  • renal failure (chronic haemoglobinaemia)
  • Thrombosis: venous and arterial thrombosis (due to complement activation.) <-leading cause of mortality
    • Dysphagia
    • Pulmonary hypertension. (50% of patients have elevated NT-pro BNP due to ? RV strain - Source
  • Diagnosis: flow cytometry : CD59 and CD55 negative cells is gold standard. Old test was the Ham test (demonstration of lysis of RBC at low pH)
  • For symptomatic PNH:
    • C5 blockers - Ravulizumab / Eculizmab (C5 blockers - prevents lysis)
      • All patients on compliments inhibitors require vaccination and prophylactic antibiotics.
    • Adequacy of C5 blockage is assessed by serum LDH levels.

Symptoms in this phase commonly involve the mucous membranes:
3. Usually begins as a pulmonary infection -> cough.
4. Can cause meningitis.(Mnemonic: "Bird brain")

  • Legionella pneumophila is a thin, aerobic, pleomorphic, flagellated, non-spore-forming, Gram-negative bacterium of the genus Legionella
  • Gram negative, intracellular
  • Pneumonia is the commonest manifestation of legionella infection. Infection of other sites is rare.
  • Causes bilateral mid to lower zone patchy consolidations.
  • Can cause mild to severe disease.
  • People get from contaminated air-conditioner water.
    • Person to person transmission doesn't occur.
  • Associated features:
    • Hyponatremia
    • Liver enzyme elevation
    • CRP > 100;
    • GI symptoms
    • Exposure (from contaminated water in buildings)
    • Resistance to beta lactams
  • Diagnosis: PCR of respiratory secretion but if this is not possible, urinary antigen can be checked.
    • Mnemonic: Comes from (air-conditioning) water and goes in water.
  • Mortality can be up to 10%.
  • Treatment: fluoquinolone or macrolide.
    • Levofloxacin - inhibits bacterial DNA topoisomerase
    • Azithromycin - 50s ribosomalal subunit and inhibit protein synthesis

Summary: ACEi / ARB -> SGLT-2 inhibitor -> Steroid as last line with poor resolution

- **RAAS inhibitors** for control of proteinuria; 
- Immunosuppessive therapy is a *last resort* because immunosuppressive therapy, while effective has significant side effects.
  • All patients with or without hypertension should receive either ACEi or ARB to reduce proteinuria and preserve renal function. If persistently proteinuric on ACEi or ARB, change to the other drug or add SGLT-2 inhibitor.
  • Tonsillectomy can reduce proteinuria and haematuria in patients with recurrent tonsilitis.

#2023GM-NOV/Q10
Viruses multiply in the muscle, enter neurons and then travel in a retrograde direction towards the CNS in motor and sensory nerves.
Hence why IG is given to muscle around the bite site.
UpToDate:

  • Site of injection:
    • Rabies vaccine should always be given to the deltoid muscle. AL thigh is acceptable in younger patients.
    • Should never be given to the gluteal area -> lower antibody titres result.
    • WHO recommends the intra dermal schedule because there is a global shortage of ARV.
    • ID site are deltoid muscle, AL thigh or suprascalpular regions.

Presentation

  • The classic presentation of encephalitic rabies includes fever, hydrophobia, pharyngeal spasms, and hyperactivity subsiding to paralysis, coma and death.
  • 20% of patients present with paralytic rabies:
  • Fewer than 20 percent of rabies patients present with an ascending paralysis, which can mimic Guillain-Barr syndrome

Diagnosis

  • Vital antigen samples can be taken from saliva, CSF, Nape of the neck skin, serum.
  • Antibodies may not show up for several days after symptoms have occured.

Major category exposure: HRIG / ERIG + ARV
HRIG is very expensive; reserved for the following:
Immunocompromised patients should recive IM ARV (and not the intradermal schedule). They often required RIG.

ARNI - Antiotensin receptor- Neprilysin inhibitor drugs

+ **Developing cirrhosis** in *background of* chronic HBV infection **massively** increases risk.
  • ALT and AST values up to 1000 to 2000 units/L are typically seen during the acute phase .
  • ALT is higher than AST.
  • The prothrombin time is the best indicator of prognosis.
    Acute HBV and HDV coinfection tends to be more severe than acute HBV infection alone and is more likely to result in fulminant hepatitis.

Key points

HBeAg is a 'pre-core' protein - a marker of active replication.

Inactive immune system -> asymptomatic chronic carrier; Active immune system -> Chronic hepatitis.

Overall, 30% of patients with cirrhosis of any cause will develop HCC.
